segments.text: 34123 tape is running and the light is on.
It says it's recording.
This is September the 21st, and down in the Wells Fargo Bank, and I have the pleasure and honor of chatting with Dean Gage.
We're going to begin about his student experiences.
Dean, to help a newcomer understand who this person is, describe your experience and all before you got to Texas A&M.
Where did you grow up?
high school, what did mom and dad do, and then where'd you go that first year and so forth?
Well, I was born and reared in the hill country in a small town called San Saba.
In fact, my mom and dad still live there.
I was the first person from either one of my families, both sides, to ever go to college or university.

And I must say that a lot of that probably was stimulated when I was in about the sixth or seventh grade in 4-H. And I came to 4-H Roundup at A&M and got to see the campus for the first time ever on a college or university campus.
I fortunately was a high point individual in a contest I want to watch and we had a terrific time here and through high school I really tried to be a high achiever and make
grades enough that clearly I could go to college if I wanted to.
So I had already come down to A&M and made the decision that I was going to study veterinary medicine.
And yet, we had a real financial need in my family.
I had already taken all the entrance exams and had been assigned a dormitory and a roommate.
was ready to come and I got two substantial scholarships one academic and the other for leadership at Tarleton State University.

My family could not pass that kind of financial benefit so I went to Tarleton my first year and roomed with another guy that I knew was going to come to A&M because he wanted to study veterinary medicine and ironically we were both
state officers in the FFA.
And knowing that A&M was the only veterinary college and knowing that we wanted to get here as soon as possible, we transferred our sophomore year.
So I arrived on this campus in the fall of 1961 and began as a student in pre-veterinary medicine at the time.
What did you, when you came, how did you get here and what did you bring?
I got here with probably one suitcase and I didn't bring much of anything with me because I didn't have hardly anything.
I brought a fan, I will tell you that, because that's all we had in the dormitories were electric fans and it was hot and all you could do is move air around a little bit.
And did you come in a car, hitchhike, train?
I did not have a car.
So I had to ride with other boys that were coming to A&M from my hometown.
Describe when you got to the campus, how did you find where you needed to be next?
How did you find which dorm?
Well, my first semester I lived in Law Hall, and I still remember to this day the assignment of that dormitory, and fortunately my good buddy and I were

rooming together, and I even remember my laundry number, GX2095 of all things, because students' laundry at that time was even done on the campus and wrapped up in brown paper, and you'd go to the laundry and pick it up.
And it was a real experience coming from a real small town.
How did you get assigned to law?
Do you know?
I don't really recall.
except through the student housing department somehow.
You were in the corps?
No, I was not in the corps because I transferred with adequate number of hours and knew that I was going to be going to veterinary college and could receive the commission without being in the corps.
And secondly, I knew that once I got into veterinary college, I could not stay in the corps.
because of the time constraints and the demands that would be upon us.
I didn't know that option existed then.
I did.
If you transferred with, I think, 30 hours or more, I never took less than 18 hours a semester.
I'll never forget Law Hall.
Describe it.
Oh, man, those rooms were just kind of like a concrete cellar that was above ground with no air circulation.
And every time the train would come down the tracks, we would know it.
And it was a community, though, within itself, because you got to know everybody on your suite and your floor.
And, you know, it was typical dormitory life.
How did you and your transfer friends get assimilated into Aggie traditions and activities?
Well, I think all of us had a pretty good background in what that was, and it did not take long to just simply get involved with campus life.
You know, just being associated with the other students in classes, and we never missed Yale practice.
We never missed muster.
We never missed Tuesday nights when we honored those silver tabs.
So we were a part of the life just by our own
election to be a part of it.
And, you know, it was only about 8,000 students then, so you had a lot of friends who were already here.
A lot of my hometown buddies were already here, a lot of them in the Corps.
Did anybody come through the dorm trying to get y'all to do anything or participate in anything?
No, I don't think they really had to.
I think there was just such a

uh loyalty of the traditions that we wanted to be a part of it so no one even really had to ask us they probably would ask us not to come because we were going to be there were their nickname was there a nickname for you guys uh not that i remember i know later on there was a nickname for the people who lived in law and puryear but i don't recall that we had any because let's see you didn't transfer into the core
So you didn't frog in.
That wouldn't work.
And you weren't a day duck.
No.
What did you all wear to class?
Generally, we wore a lot of Western wear back then because so many of my classmates and me had mostly boots and either Levi's or Wranglers and just regular sports shirts.
But we took pride in how we looked.
And we, you know, dressed up.
There were no shorts.
There were no tank tops and really no T-shirts.
We took pride in how we looked.

Plus, all of us who had the plans to go to veterinary college knew that once we entered veterinary college, we were going to be wearing a tie and a dress shirt every day or medical uniforms once we got there.
Were there any memorable courses you took that first year?
Oh yeah, there were several.
I took one in physics that was so memorable, mainly because of the demeanor of the professor in there.
I think he had three shirts and maybe two ties and he wore them, it seemed like, every other day.
And he was red-headed, and one of his ties was brown, the other was orange, and it just kind of all was a part of his esprit de corps.
And he was one of these high intellectuals that could really teach, but to carry on a conversation sometimes is a little difficult.
And then I had Dr. Harris in history, and he made it very interesting with some of his stories, particularly about Guadalcanal, and a lot of his antics preceded him before we got in class with him.
So in the pre-veterinary, those were the two most memorable ones.
I'll tell you one that was memorable was biochemistry.
It was a tough course, but the reason it's memorable
It was over where the dairy lab was and we always got ice cream either before after class free.
No, we had to pay for it and What describe that first year?
Describe a typical class days routine.
What did you?
What time did you get up?
What did you do?
Where?
When?
Well, we took heavy loads, and I had a goal of getting into veterinary college in two years.
So that meant that I'd already had one year with 36 or 37 transfer hours, and I wanted to package into that second year, my first year here at A&M, my sophomore year, as many hours as I could

to get the requirements completed so that i could get in in two years so my days were very long because i took 18 19 hours and i i thoroughly though did like to take the early morning classes and i had most eight hour i mean eight o'clock classes of a morning
And by the time you take that many hours, you're pretty well filled up with lecture, and then it's very heavy in the sciences, so I had a lot of laboratories.
I had organic chemistry, biochemistry, all of that in the same time frame.
So the days were packed predominantly with either lectures or labs, a few hours off in which that was time to do the things you had to do, your laundry and other parts.
But I guarantee you we took time out for football games, for Yale practice, for the Aggie activities of the day.
We never failed to participate in those.
But when it got to be 7 o'clock at night, I was studying.
I was burning the midnight oil.
Where did you study?
I predominantly studied in my room.
I was fortunate to be a person that developed great study habits in high school.
And if I could get it quiet and I could take my set of notes and take the book and go through it and highlight it and mark it, I could memorize things by going over it a couple of times.
And I studied mostly in the dormitory.
So it was quiet enough.
It was quiet enough, mm-hmm.
And you ate in?
Sebesa.
Describe it.
Oh, man, there were some real food riots, and you can imagine what all happened in Sebesa and food fights and, you know, of course, terrific food there.
And all the food was labeled, as I'm sure many others have already told you, and it was just a sight to behold with that many thousand people in there together eating at one time.
What was your favorite Aggie food?
Oh, my.
Probably chicken fried steak.
Was there one at the other end of the spectrum that you didn't like?
I did not like meatloaf, and to this day I don't like meatloaf.
What's the nickname for it?
I don't remember it.
Oh, I don't either.
I don't remember what it was.
And chicken flapjack didn't have a nickname.
Not that I know of, unless it was cow or something.
I think it was, I think most of the time we had beef, it was called cow or bull.
I don't remember.
And bull neck was...
What was it?
Steak, wasn't it?
Yeah, yeah.
Bullneck was steak.
Yeah, bullneck was steak.
And y'all didn't have any routine at your table or anything like that?
No.
You were civilian students.
No, we mainly went in.
I'll tell you one other thing I remember about my sophomore year.
There were no computers, and registration was quite a process because it was held in Sabeasa.
And it was every person for themselves, and you know, you knew the reputation of the different professors, so you wanted to try to match your schedule to a professor that had a good reputation.

but you were at the mercy you had a card with your schedule on it and you had to work it out you had to work out the courses you took you had to work out who the professor would be and the times that you took those so it is a real challenge and you'd go back and forth and you know you'd also try to get the same course schedule your buddies had so it was quite a quite an ordeal remember to whom you turned for advice to be sure you were taking the right course yeah i do because uh
The university did a good job there.
We had undergraduate advisors, and at that time, if we were pre-vet, we actually had someone in the veterinary college who was an advisor to us on the courses that we took.
Do you remember who that was?
I do not remember who mine was.
But I do remember that Dr. McMurray, Associate Dean for Academic Affairs, helped almost every one of us.
Compare the rigor of the courses here that year
compared to the previous year at Tarleton?
There really was very little difference, which surprised me.
I was fortunate to have come from a high school that had very, very high standards.
And I was so well prepared for my first year of college that I sailed through it.
I even had organic chemistry in high school.
And we could go into chemistry 101, 102.
I didn't even have to do the experiments.
I already knew the answers.
And my other classmates from my own high school, they were all in the same boat.
So it was rigorous, and particularly the biologies.
They were harder.
But we had great preparation, and it gave me great preparation for here.
Let's see, during that year before vet school, in the dormitory, were there any pranks or jokes or?
When I was at Tarleton?
Or here?
Somebody set a trash can on fire half the time.
There were water balloon fights.
I don't remember any specific big one.
I tell you what, most of us trying to get into veterinary college, we had such a fear that if we got involved in anything, that we might not get in.
And at that time, they only took 64 students, and they were having about 600 applications.
So we pretty well walked a straight and narrow path.
Now, there was no formal organization of the pre-vets.
No.
There was a prescribed pre-veterinary medical track, but not like now where you have a biomedical science degree.
It was clearly different then.
We're still for a few minutes talking only about your second year of college, first one here.
What did you assume were the rules of classroom behavior here at A&M?
It was clear that the professor was keen of the classroom, and you gave that professor utmost respect.
You called the professor, yes, sir, or if it was a lady, you called them, yes, ma'am, or addressed them that way, sir and ma'am, and yes, sir, yes, ma'am.
You were in class on time and in your seat.
If not, you were really afraid to walk in late.
There was great respect and complete discipline.
You did not talk in class.
You paid attention.
You took notes.
But at the same time, they were approachable.
They were friendly.
They were helpful.
And they had a heart to see us learn.
And they had, I think, a real interest in what we were trying to pursue as a degree.
And that was really noted in some of the tough courses.
Organic chemistry, for one.

most of the organic chemistry professors had a reputation of being tough and hard but at the same time they were very fair and they were very helpful and one of them and I will never forget this his name was Rakoff and he had the reputation of
and I had him, of coming in and passing out a major exam and telling you what his dog made on that exam.
And I made A's in organic, but the poor guy next to me, on one of the exams, he passed it out, and he said his dog made 48 on it, and the guy next to me made 24.
And it was tough, but it was fair.
Did the MSC have any role in that year in your life pattern?
You'd be surprised what I would say about the MSC because it was quite small back then.
The major thing it had, one, it had the only telephones where you could make long-distance phone calls.
And secondly is the only place I knew where you could go cash a check.
As far as the MSC programs, I really was not involved in those simply because I didn't have time and I was trying to get in in two years.
And I really devoted most of my time to trying to make the highest grades I could.

they were at the Grove and and I'm trying to remember was Guyon Hall still there in 61 I believe it was I don't remember ever going to a movie in Guyon Hall but I went to some movies over at the Grove what about you go to campus theater much

a few times and then we went downtown brian to the old palace and queen and and i'll tell you what to eat in this town you only had a few places other than a few places in northgate uh the wormans downtown young bloods uh you went to barbecue which was
I think over kind of where the Hilton Hotel is now.
That was it.
And the Texan was the drive-in.
Texan was the drive-in, and I got to tell you one more.
That was the Tasty Freeze.
And every night at 1030, we often would go in some of the cars, we'd drive over the Tasty Freeze, and we would get
a Frito Pie, which was made by taking a bag of Fritos, pouring cheese, onions, and stirring it up into a Frito Pie.
And that was it.
The Frosted Mugs.
Did you get involved in any campus religious activities?
I did at the Baptist Church College Station.
But on Saturdays, I went to school church.
I never failed.
It was one church behind me.
It was a veterinary
after church one day and asked me if I wanted a date with his sister for the Arkansas football game.
And of course I didn't have a date and there were no girls or very few girls here at the time and I said sure.
So that's where it's starting.
Really?
It really is.
Describe that weekend date then.
Well, actually I was already in veterinary college.
I was in my second year.
That's all right.
Go ahead.
And she was, of all places, the University of Texas.
But she had wanted to come to A&M but could not come to A&M because girls were not allowed.
But her oldest brother was here and he arranged and called her that, yeah, come on over.
And she brought a friend with her from the University of Texas.
And I had a roommate that needed a date.
So we were in the MSC lobby waiting on them to arrive on Friday afternoon.
And when she started walking up, the two of them, I should say, I looked at both of them and I said, I hope that that one on the right is his sister because I didn't want to go with the other one.
And sure enough, it was.
And it was a wonderful time that we had together.
Had you seen a picture of her before?
No, I had not.
So I wasn't sure.
So we went to old Coach Norton's restaurant Friday night and had dinner.
And we just began to hit it off.
She stayed with the Heaton's, who was registrar here.
she had known their daughter at University of Texas, Kathleen.
So that's where she stayed that night, and then the next day we went to the football game, and I don't remember all that we did, but we went to the football game.
Of course, A&M did not win.
Did they score any touchdowns, though?
I don't think so.
We almost were at point of kissing on first downs back then.
As a student, I never saw a winning football season.
Oh, that's right.
Never.
the whole time I was a student here.
And only the year after I left, which would have been the 67th football season, they won the conference.
So I never saw that until I came back here as a faculty member.
But did you kiss this girl on that?
I kissed her on the first night.
On that first date?
I did.
Do you remember among your friends,
of that era, do you remember hearing any stories of inappropriate behavior of Aggies and blind dates?
No, never.
Aggies were taught, and I think that this is something that is very true of the values that were inculcated in most Aggies and are still
coming predominantly from their homes and families, that they were taught to respect women and ladies.
And I never heard of any of that at all.
I never saw any of it.
Generalize about the attitudes of the students at A&M that you think they possessed
at that time?
I really think they came with a tremendous conservative value system that placed a high priority on God, family, and country.
Most of us at that time were offsprings of World War II veterans.
Not only World War II veterans, but parents who lived through
the ending years of the Great Depression and the enormous sacrifices that many of them made to be able to send us to college.
And we had probably such a grateful heart for what our families and our parents had provided us.
We also came here with a commitment that we would not let them down.
because we knew it was a sacrifice.

And I can remember, particularly when I got into veterinary college my first year, that near the end of the semester, every once in a while, I would have to sell a textbook to have enough money to eat for the rest of the semester.
Do you remember what that first year cost in round numbers?
Oh, I have no idea, but I'll tell you what I remember about tuition in my freshman year.
It was $40 a semester.
My first year here at A&M, everyone just went berserk because it doubled to $80 a semester, regardless of the number of hours that you took.
And I really don't recall it going up a great deal in 61, I mean in 62, but when I entered veterinary college, that was a little higher tuition rate.
I don't remember what that was.
Did you have spending money?
And if so, where'd you get it?
I had very little spending money.
Most of my spending money was for food.
And, you know, I had a little, and then I got it predominantly from my mom and dad.
I later, when I was in veterinary college, worked at the large animal hospital and was able to pick up a little bit of money there.
Now, before you made that formal application to vet school, who did you turn to for advice and counsel on how to do it?
It was pretty well prescribed by the dean's office in the veterinary medical college.
And then I had a dear friend who was a former state congressman from San Angelo named Penrose Metcalf.
And he had helped young men for probably 30, 40, 50 years.
He was an Aggie.
And I had gotten to know him because of my state leadership roles in high school.
And he seemed to pick out young men who were in leadership roles in high school
that he thought would make a good student at A&M.
And he really helped guide and would tell me things I needed to do, particularly not having parents that knew the ropes of what to do in a college or university setting.
And then secondly, my hometown veterinarian gave me some counsel and advice on some certain things to do.
And then I just was fortunate to have high enough grades
that I was one of the first 13 to get letters out of that 64 selected in that class.
Do you remember what your GPA was?
It was a 3.8.
Other than the paper application, what else was involved in the process of selection?
Well, I was fortunate because at that time,
They would take the first few highest ones based upon what their academic performance was, what their grades were in the hard science courses, the biologies, the physics, the organic.
And secondly, they looked at what your leadership had been.
And I had a pretty substantial resume of leadership, even my first year at Tarleton.
I was elected president of the student FFA chapter up there.
I'd been on the collegiate livestock judging team and had some other position of leadership.
So that was part of my resume coming to it.
I didn't even have to have an interview.
Now, when they got to about the last half of that class of 64, then they did do interviews.
And, of course, now they interview every student.
How did you learn you'd been selected?
I'll never forget this.
Everyone was waiting.
We'd heard the letters were going to come out.

I had gone home for the weekend and I came back and the first thing I did when I got back on campus was to go to the post office at Northgate and open my mailbox and there was the letter from Dean Price.
And you can imagine
I probably didn't take more than 10 steps jumping all the way to the MSC to call my mom and dad.
I still have that letter to this day.
And that was about when in the spring?
That would have been probably about April of the spring semester.
Of course, that was contingent upon successful completion of the courses I was enrolled in.
And what did you do that summer?
I went back home and worked.
On the farm?
On the farm and ranch.
Helped my dad, which I had done every summer.
